column1: In an attempt to reduce the incidence of NSAID - induced gastrointestinal lesions , the following approaches have been proposed : ( i ) use of the prostaglandin analogue misoprostol , which is an antiulcer drug which has been proven to be as effective in the prevention of NSAID - induced gastric and duodenal ulcers as in the reduction of serious upper gastrointestinal complications ; ( ii ) histamine H2 receptor antagonists ( H2 antagonists ) , e . g . ranitidine , cimetidine and famotidine , which are useful in the prevention of NSAID - induced duodenal ulcers during long term treatment , but not in the prevention of NSAID - induced gastric ulcers ; ( iii ) proton pump inhibitors , e . g omeprazole , and pantoprazole , whose efficacy in preventing NSAID - associated ulcers has been recently demonstrated ; and ( iv ) barrier agents , e . g . sucralfate , which cannot be recommended as prophylactic agents to prevent NSAID - induced gastropathy .
